Duck Typing is a programming concept that states that the type or class of an object is determined by its behavior rather than its inheritance from a particular class or interface. In other words, if an object behaves like a duck (quacks like a duck, walks like a duck), then it is considered a duck, regardless of its actual type or class.

In TypeScript, Duck Typing can be achieved through the use of interfaces. An interface in TypeScript is a collection of method signatures and property types that define the expected behavior and structure of an object. When implementing an interface, a class must provide implementations for all the methods and properties defined in the interface. If an object behaves like the interface, it can be considered as implementing that interface, regardless of its actual type or class.

Here's an example to illustrate Duck Typing in TypeScript:

```typescript
interface Quackable {
  quack(): void;
}

class Duck implements Quackable {
  quack(): void {
    console.log("Quack!");
  }
}

class Squeakable {
  squeak(): void {
    console.log("Squeak!");
  }
}

function performQuack(quackable: Quackable): void {
  quackable.quack();
}

const duck: Quackable = new Duck();
performQuack(duck); // Output: Quack!

const squeakable: Squeakable = new Squeakable();
// performQuack(squeakable); // This will result in a compile-time error because Squeakable does not implement the Quackable interface
```

